{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0f1a89ea-f132-4c66-9f68-6c69355aa1da","content":"Your project isn't in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your server.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, that's typically `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will prompt you to start the server. You can also manage it via the **MCP: List Servers** command in the command palette.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"02adc8a5-96cf-42de-8857-11b768bac65f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user says they built it. They're asking how to configure mcp.json, so I'll provide the configuration guidance.","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"3C09:1C1C65:1EB9C00:22A0C83:69E81CDC"},"id":"69b8e29e-e270-4f42-ba0f-57ce7be8fa53","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:08.864Z","parentId":"3768202c-9b0b-4d74-9a8b-ec96aabe90d1"}
